<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="128" type="discussion">
<paragraph pageId="5" pageNumber="128">
Comments: Little needs to be added to Melander’s description. Females have a slightly different colour pattern to males; the scutal pattern is less distinct, and the abdominal tergites have variable grey markings on the anterior regions of tergites 1 —4. The male genitalia are illustrated in 
<captionCitation box="[776,932,747,787]" captionStartId="3.[5,63,2265,2296]" pageId="5" pageNumber="128">Figs 5-7</captionCitation>
The female from Willowmore (
<collectionCode box="[26,150,797,828]" collectionName="South Africa, Kwa-Zulu Natal, Pietermaritzburg, Natal Museum" pageId="5" pageNumber="128">NMSA</collectionCode>
) is labelled ‘ type’, but was collected in 1912, long after Melander’s 1907 description.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="5" pageNumber="128">
<taxonomicName box="[52,239,899,930]" class="Insecta" family="Apioceridae" genus="Apiocera" genus.bestMatchDistance="689" genus.bestMatchVote="2" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="128" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="braunsi">
A. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[106,239,899,930]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="128">braunsi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is more common in collections than 
<taxonomicName box="[902,1080,899,930]" class="Insecta" family="Apioceridae" genus="Apiocera" genus.bestMatchDistance="1293" genus.bestMatchVote="2" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="128" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alastor">
A. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[957,1080,899,930]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="128">alastor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and has been collected at a larger number of localities. The striking, similar colour patterns of the scutum and abdomen in 
<emphasis box="[301,433,999,1030]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="128">braunsi</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis box="[519,644,999,1030]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="128">alastor</emphasis>
(Figs 1-2), indicates they are sister species.
</paragraph>
